In the paper, authors assume two generations per year

Generation time of 1 year is questionable since Daphnia can have shorter asexual cycles. Omilian & Lynch 2005 used 5 generations per year in Daphnia (http://www.indiana.edu/~lynchlab/PDF/Lynch170.pdf), as did Walser and Haag 2012 (http://www.unifr.ch/biol/ecology/haag/pdfs/Walser_and_Haag_2012.pdf), the latter citing Ebert 2005 "Ecology, epidemiology, and evolution of parasitism in Daphnia" (a book).

According correspondence with Baker (2019) gtime is variable. file: “Jbaker correspondence5d.pdf” shows a table of gtimes for this lake during this period. The gtime average for whole period (1986-2015) is 1.3976. The average for the specific timeframe (1990-2009) is 1.333. The correspondence with Aguirre (2012) agrees that the gtime is between 1 and 2 years (0.5 to 1 generations a year).

from Reznick 1997: "Guppies breed throughout the year and have overlapping generations. We estimated generation time T using the life table method, which is based on estimates of birth and death schedules in natural populations. We estimated mortality rates from mark-recapture experiments on guppies from seven low-predation localities, including the Aripo and El Cedro experimental sites. Because the life table method requires age-specific survival, we estimated the ages of individuals in different size classes using growth rate equations derived for the same fish in the mark-recapture experiments based on their sizes at the beginning and end of the recapture interval. We estimated size-specific fecundity with dissections and embryo counts from females collected from these same localities, plus from additional collections. We estimated the frequency of reproduction from laboratory studies, conducted at temperatures and food availabilities similar to those in the field. With this information, we estimated the mean generation time of fish in low-predation localities to be 210 days, or 1.74 generations per year". So, gtime=0.575.

According to Nur Aida et al 2008 (Trop Biomed 25(2): 117-125), the generation time is 20.14 days (0.055 years), but this is in the lab. It does not take into account the winter in USA. According Waldock et al 2013 (Pathogens and Global Health 107(5): 224-241) in North America, a photoperiod of 13:11 (L:D) induces diapause in Ae. albopictus. I (gorne) computed the number generations in one year according to the number of days longer than 13 hours in one year. Then computed the generation time as the average of the gtime (reciprocal of the number of generations in one year) in both locations. i.e. Florida 5.38 G/y (113 days), Texas 5.81 G/y (122 days), New York 6.95 G/y (146 days).

From the paper (Carrol 1997): Generation time is about 40 d (measured in captivity at 30 ºC). There is a large difference between the host species in the annual pattern of seed availability. In the introduced host, a much larger seed crop is available for a much briefer annual period, while in the native host, smaller seed crops are available year-round. There is time for two or three generations of bugs to develop on the introduced host, while more generations may develop in the Keys on the native host depending on how individual bugs move among sequential seed crops on different host individuals. We take the generation time on the new host (gorne 2022).

Beckers, O. M., Anderson, W. and Moczek, A. P. (2015), A combination of developmental plasticity, parental effects, and genetic differentiation mediates divergences in life history traits between dung beetle populations. Evolution & Development, 17: 148�159. doi:10.1111/ede.12117

Under good conditions Onthophagus taurus display 2 generations each year (https://www.ukbeetles.co.uk/onthophagus-taurus). The adults are active from early spring to late autumn, they pair up in the spring. The development is rapid and under optimum conditions of nutrition and temperature the cycle from egg to adult takes eight to ten weeks, there are often two generations each year and in warmer climates this is the norm. Well fed and later instar larvae will overwinter in the brood chamber, continuing to feed in mild spells and producing very early spring adults. Those that eclose and emerge in the autumn will return to the burrow to overwinter.

Form the paper (Hill 1999): "P. aegeria develops continuously on Madeira (four to five generations per year) but only develops through 1.5 generations per year in Yorkshire (Blakeley 1996). This would result in approximately 100 generations since colonization for subspecies aegeria (and possibly more if P. aegeria arrived on Madeira before 1976), but only 30 generations for tircis."

Generation Time according to Engler et al 2009 (Engler R, Randin CF, Vittoz P, Czáka T, Beniston M, Zimmermann NE & Guisan A. 2009. Predicting future distributions of mountain plants under climate change: does dispersal capacity matter?. Ecography, 32:34-45) is 2 years. However, it is long lived perennial plant. Only 13% of the Achillea plants flowered during the 2 years, and no plant flowered twice (Bostock SJ & Benton RA. 1979. The Reproductive Strategies of Five Perennial Compositae. The Journal of Ecology, 67:91-107). So, a generation time of 3 years is still a underestimation. Generation time as the number of years required for a species to start producing seeds can underestimate the actual generation time. Transition matrix in COMPADRE database includes vegetative reproduction (ramet transition matrix), so generation time cannot be computed (it is infinite).

Lotus purshianus, a dicot, is an annual herb. It flowers in spring (to early summer) (https://www.calflora.org/app/taxon?crn=10961). Seeds do not have primary dormancy (Guerrant Jr EO & Raven A. 1995. Seed germination and storability studies of 69 plant taxa native to the Willamette Valley wet prairie. Portland, OR: The Berry Botanic Garden). So, generation time is one year.

It is an annual plant with seed physcal dormancy, so generation time it is assumend to be 1 year. Authors said 4/10 plots elapsed 2 generations and 6/10 plots elapsed 1 generation. This is why time mesured in generations is not exactly the same as time (years) over GT.

Generation time computed from COMPADRE database transition matrices (Matrices 241455, 241459, 241463, 241467, 241471, 241475, 241479, 241483, 241487, 241491, 241495, 241499, 241454, 241453, 241450, 241451, 241452 in COMPADRE Plant Matrix Database (2021). Available from: https://www.compadre-db.org/Species/46616 [20 May 2021, Version 6.21.1.0]). Plants live a year or less and flowered in their second year (Byers DL & Quinn JA. 1998. Demographic variation in Alliaria petiolata (Brassicaceae) in four contrasting habitats. Journal of the Torrey Botanical Society, 125:138-149). Seeds do not germinate in the same growing season because they need cold stratification (Anderson RC, Dhillion SS & Kelley TM. 1996. Aspects of the Ecology of an Invasive Plant, Garlic Mustard (Alliaria petiolata), in Central Illinois. Restoration Ecology, 4:181–191).

Ambrosia artemisiifolia is a wind-pollinated, monoecious annual herb, which germinates in the spring and sets fruit in the autumn. Ambrosia artemisiifolia is sensitive to freezing. Late spring frosts kill seedlings and the first autumn frosts terminate the growing season. Ambrosia artemisiifolia forms a persistent soil seed bank as aresult of complex germination strategies. Seeds are dormant following their dispersal in autumn. This primary (innate) dormancy is then broken by low winter temperatures (optimallya few days around 4°C) and seeds that donot germinate the next spring enter secondary (induced) dormancy (Essl F, Biró K, Brandes D, Broennimann O, Bullock JM, Chapman DS, ... & Follak S. 2015. Biological flora of the British Isles: Ambrosia artemisiifolia. Journal of Ecology 103: 1069-1098). So, generation time is 1 year.
NA

Barbarea vulgaris is biannual, requires to overwinter to flower (vernalization) and seeds are induced to dormancy, minimum size of rosettes are required to vernalized. So, flowering, fruiting, germination and vegetative stage cannot be reached in a single growing season (Macdonald MA. 1977. Effects Of Environmental Heterogeneity On The Abundance Of Barbarea Vulgaris Rbr. Doctoral disertation. University of Western Ontario, London, Ontario, Canada.)

Authors guess that "one or two generations" have elapsed in the 70 years (Eränen 2009, Journal of Evolutionary Biology 22: 840-851). Transition matrix in COMPADRE database is one of shoots (ramets) transition matrix not one of individuals (genets) transition matrix. So, generation time can no be computed. We assume generation time equal to 70/1.5

Generation time computed as the age at which members of a given cohort are expected to reproduce according to demographic data from Fair et al (Fair J, Lauenroth WK & Coffin DP. 1999. Demography of Bouteloua gracilis in a mixed prairie: analysis of genets and individuals. Journal of Ecology, 87:233-243)

Generation Time computed with data from (Hæggström CA & Skytén R. 1996. Flowering and individual survival of a population of the grass Brachypodium sylvaticum in Nåtö, Åland Islands, SW Finland. Annales Botanici Fennici, 33:1-10). GT is likely to be underestimated because the followed cohorts did not reach their maximum lifespan and because seed production was assumed evenly distributed among age classes each year.

Not in the paper, but this is an annual species. In the literature I did not find information about seed dormancy or vernalization requirements of the species. Generation time could be shorter than 1 year.
NA

Bromus madritensis is an annual species with no persistent seedbank (Salo LF. 2004. Population dynamics of red brome (Bromus madritensis subsp. rubens): times for concern, opportunities for management. Journal of Arid Environments 57: 291-296).

Generation time as the “The age at which members of a given cohort are expected to reproduce”, computed with data from: Dietz H, Fischer M & Schmid B. 1999. Demographic and genetic invasion history of a 9-year-old roadside population of Bunias orientalis L.(Brassicaceae). Oecologia, 120:225-234.

Diploid plants of Butomus umbellatus flowered after the first winter (Hroudová Z & Zákravský P. 1993. Ecology of two cytotypes of Butomus umbellatus II. Reproduction, growth and biomass production. Folia Geobotanica et Phytotaxonomica 28: 413-424). But the plants keep alive ad flowering at least for 5 years (Hroudová Z. 1989. Growth of Butomus umbellatus at a stable water level. Folia Geobotanica et Phytotaxonomica 24: 371-385). Additionally, it reproduces abundantly by bulbids (vegetativelly). So, a generation time of 1 year is a underestimation.

One generation take place in ane year (Yatsu Y, Kachi N & Kudoh H. 2003. Ecological distribution and phenology of an invasive species, Cardamine hirsuta L., and its native counterpart, Cardamine flexuosa With., in central Japan. Plant Species Biology, 18:35-42)

Generation time averaged from the estimation from different sources. First, it was computed with data from Woodburn TL & Sheppard AW. 1996. The demography of Carduus nutans as a native and an alien weed. Plant Protection Quarterly, 11:236-238. Second, with transitions matrix from COMPADRE database (Matrices 242153, 242147, 242151, 242152 in COMPADRE Plant Matrix Database (2021). Available from: https://www.compadre-db.org/Species/46679 [17 May 2021, Version 6.21.1.0]).

All but 3% of plants flowered and produce seeds in the first year (García Y, Callaway RM, Diaconu A, Montesinos D. 2013. Invasive and non-invasive congeners show similar trait shifts between their same native and non-native ranges. PLoS ONE, 8:e82281). Centaurea calcitrapa is an annual to short-lived perennial with no evidence of seed dormancy (Pitcairn MJ, Young JA, Clements CD & Balciunas JOE. 2002. Purple starthistle (Centaurea calcitrapa) seed germination. Weed Technology, 16:452-456). It is monocarpic, mostly annual (Weeds Australia Database at www.weeds.org.au).

Life history of C. diffusa range frome annual to short living perenial and a proportion of its seeds have no dormancy. So GT was computed with age at flowering from Thompson & Stout 1991 (Thompson DJ & Stout DG. 1991. Duration of the juvenile period in diffuse knapweed (Centaurea diffusa). Canadian Journal of Botany, 69:368–371). C. diffusa, like other semelparous perennials, flowers after reaching a critical rosette size. The age at which reproduction takes place thus depends on how fast the rosette grow (Powell RD. 1990. The Role of Spatial Pattern in the Population Biology of Centaurea Diffusa. The Journal of Ecology, 78:374-388). C. diffusa reproduces exclusively by seed. Approximately 95% of seedling recruitment takes place during late April (spring) when the ground is moist and temperatures are moderate, the remainder occurs in late September (autum). Spring seedling survival is initially high, but declines rapidly with the onset of the summer drought. The vegetative rosette stage persists for several years before semelparous flowering in dense populations (Powell RD. 1990. The Role of Spatial Pattern in the Population Biology of Centaurea Diffusa. The Journal of Ecology, 78:374-388). C. diffusa requires vernalization (overwinter) to flower (Thompson DJ & Stout DG. 1991. Duration of the juvenile period in diffuse knapweed (Centaurea diffusa). Canadian Journal of Botany, 69:368–371). Each individual plant of C. diffusa can produce seeds with no primary dormancy or different levels of primary dormancy (NOLAN DG & UPADHYAYA MK. 1988. Primary seed dormancy in diffuse and spotted knapweed. Canadian Journal of Plant Science, 68:775-783)

Centaurea stoebe L. (syn. C. maculosa Lam., Asteraceae) is a short-lived herb native to Europe. It exists as two cytotypes, diploid (2n=18) and tetraploid (2n=36). Diploids are mainly monocarpic, flowering in the first or second year, whereas tetraploids are predominantly polycarpic and start flowering in the first year (Hahn MA, Van Kleunen M & Müller-Schärer H. 2012. Increased phenotypic plasticity to climate may have boosted the invasion success of polyploid Centaurea stoebe. PloS one, 7:e50284). Generation time computed according Broz et al 2009, as the average of diploid and tetraploids populations (Broz AK, Manter DK, Bowman G, Müller-Schärer H & Vivanco JM. 2009. Plant origin and ploidy influence gene expression and life cycle characteristics in an invasive weed. BMC Plant Biology, 9:1-13). The maximum lifespan for tetraploid individuals is 9 years (Boggs KW & Story JM. 1987. The population age structure of spotted knapweed (Centaurea maculosa) in Montana. Weed Science, 35:194-198). Generation time was computed from COMPADRE database transition matrices (Matrices 239512, 239513, 239514, 239515, 239516, 239517, 239518, 239519, 239520, 239521, 239522, 239523 in COMPADRE Plant Matrix Database (2021). Available from: https://www.compadre-db.org/Species/46345 [20 May 2021, Version 6.21.1.0])

Centaurea melitensis is a winter annual germinate and flowered in one year (Porras R & Munoz JM. 2000. Cleistogamy in Centaurea melitensis (Asteraceae): capitulum variability and spatio-temporal development patterns. Plant Systematics and Evolution, 223:251-262). Seed dormancy is variable and incompleate within each individual (Porras R & Muñoz JM. 2000. Achene heteromorphism in the cleistogamous species Centaurea melitensis. Acta Oecologica, 21:231-243), so seeds can germinate in the same growing season. In mediterranean climate, Centaurea melitensis have one generation each year.

All plants flowered and produced seeds in the first year (García Y, Callaway RM, Diaconu A, Montesinos D. 2013. Invasive and non-invasive congeners show similar trait shifts between their same native and non-native ranges. PLoS ONE, 8:e82281). Plants germinate in Autumn, stay as a rosette in winter and flowered late in summer (Thomsen CD. 1996. Yellow starthistle biology and control Vol. 21541 UCANR Publications). Centaurea solstitialis requires about 2140 degree days (over 2 ºC) for 50% of the plants to reach seed dispersal, It does not require vernalization to flower (Roche CT, Thill DC & Shafii B. 1997. Reproductive phenology in yellow starthistle (Centaurea solstitialis). Weed Science, 45:763-770). Seeds do not show primary (innate) dormancy, but secondary induced (Joley DB, Maddox DM, Schoenig SE & Mackey BE. 2003. Parameters affecting germinability and seed bank dynamics in dimorphic achenes of Centaurea solstitialis in California. Canadian Journal of Botany, 81:993-1007). So, generation time can be shorter than a year in warm non-stational climates.

All plants flowered and produced seeds in the first year (García Y, Callaway RM, Diaconu A, Montesinos D. 2013. Invasive and non-invasive congeners show similar trait shifts between their same native and non-native ranges. PLoS ONE, 8:e82281). C. sulphurea germinates in the fall and grow vegetatively as rosettes until they bolt in late spring and produce flowering stems. Individual flowers are grouped into heads that are produced for three to four weeks. There is no evidence of seed dormancy (Gerlach Jr JD & Rice KJ. 2003. Testing life history correlates of invasiveness using congeneric plant species. Ecological applications, 13:167-179). So, generation time can be shorter than a year in warm non-stational climates.
Not in the paper. Not found in the literature

Lactuca muralis a herbaceous perennial hemicryptophyte. The plant is winter green dying completely back after flowering in the summer but then producing a small overwintering rosette(s) from a bud(s) on the rootstock. The plant is generally not monocarpic. Reproduction is entirely by seed. Most seeds germinate in the autumn and overwinter as a small rosette although some germinate in the following spring. Newly shed achenes germinate readily, giving rise in nature to seedling populations immediately after the flowering period. Seeds may also germinate after overwintering in the following spring. Flowering is possible after one season providing plants reach an appropriate size. After flowering the plant dies back completely, but in the autumn anover wintering rosette is produced from a bud or buds on the rootstock (Clabby G & Osborne BA. 1999. Mycelis muralis (L.) Dumort.(Lactuca muralis (L.) Gaertner). Journal of ecology, 87:156-172). There is no information about the lifespan of each individual through the new rootstock rosettes. So, the minimum generation time is one year (this can underestimate the actual generation time).

Cichorium intybus L. is a biennial plant. In order to be florally induced, chicory must undergo an exposure to low temperature (3 weeks at 4 °C) that can be applied to germinating seeds or to the entire plant. Under natural conditions, chicory plants are vernalized during the winter, and subsequently bolt and flower in the second growing season (Demeulemeester MAC & De Proft MP. 1999. In vivo and in vitro flowering response of chicory (Cichorium intybus L.): influence of plant age and vernalization. Plant Cell Reports, 18:781-785). Chicory is a monocarpic species (Keller M & Kollmann J. 1999. Effects of seed provenance on germination of herbs for agricultural compensation sites. Agriculture, ecosystems & environment, 72:87-99). Cichorium intybus seeds do not show any dormancy (Corbineau F & Come D. 1990. Germinability and quality of Cichorium intybus L. seeds. In VI Symposium on the Timing of Field Production of Vegetables 267:183-190). So, generation time is one year.

Crepis sancta is a Mediterranean annual herb of Asteraceae family. Germination occurs in the autumn with the onset of the rainy season, flowering occurs in early spring, lasts for 5-8 weeks and seeds are produced shortly after (Dener E, Shemesh H & Giladi I. 2021. The effect of pollen source on seed traits and dispersability in the heterocarpic annual Crepis sancta. Journal of Plant Ecology, 14:425–437). No primary dormancy is observed in Crepis sancta's seeds (Imbert E, Escarre J & Lepart J. 1996. Achene dimorphism and among-population variation in Crepis sancta (Asteraceae). International Journal of Plant Sciences, 157:309-315). So, generation time is one year.

Cynoglossum officinale (Boraginaceae) is a monocarpic perennial. None of the plants flowered in their first season, despite their large size, indicating that all plants had a vernalization requirement (WESSELINGH RA, DE JONG TJ, KLINKHAMER PGL, VAN DIJK MJ & SCHLATMANN EGM. 1993. Geographical variation in threshold size for flowering inCynoglossum officinale. Acta Botanica Neerlandica, 42:81–91). Most of the seeds germinate in the first spring following maturation (no seed dormancy). None of the plants flowered in the first year, mortality probability and flowering remain constant after seedling stage, %5 of plants from a cohort flowered in the second year (1 year old) and 7% in the thirth year (2 years old) (De Jong TJ & Klinkhamer PG. 1988. Population ecology of the biennials Cirsium vulgare and Cynoglossum officinale in a coastal sand-dune area. The Journal of Ecology, 76:366-382). Plants may grow vegetatively for 4-5 years before reproducing (de Jong TJ & Klinkhamer PG. 1989. Limiting factors for seed production in Cynoglossum officinale. Oecologia, 80:167-172). Generation matrix was computed from COMPADRE database transition matrix (Matrix 242577 in COMPADRE Plant Matrix Database (2021). Available from: https://www.compadre-db.org/Species/46610 [20 May 2021, Version 6.21.1.0])

Generation time computed from the COMPADRE database transition matrix (Matrix 246495 in COMPADRE Plant Matrix Database (2021). Available from: https://www.compadre-db.org/Species/46350 [18 May 2021, Version 6.21.1.0])) based on the work of Parker 1996 (Parker IM. 1996. Ecological factors affecting rates of spread in Cytisus scoparius, an invasive exotic shrub. Doctoral dissertation. University of Washintong)

Generation Time is considered as the number of years required for a species to start producing seeds (this can underestimate the actual generation time) according to: Engler R, Randin CF, Vittoz P, Czáka T, Beniston M, Zimmermann NE & Guisan A. 2009. Predicting future distributions of mountain plants under climate change: does dispersal capacity matter?. Ecography, 32:34-45.

Datura stramonium is an annual plant (Núnez‐Farfán J, Cabrales‐Vargas RA & Dirzo R. 1996. Mating system consequences on resistance to herbivory and life history traits in Datura stramonium. American Journal of Botany, 83:1041-1049) and its seeds have primary physical and physiological dormancy (Brown NAC & Bridglall SS. 1987. Preliminary studies of seed dormancy in Datura stramonium. South African Journal of Botany, 53:107-109). Without treatment, the physiological dormancy remains for 6 months and physical dormancy requires scarification (Mu X, Shi L, Zhao Y, Duan L & Lei J. 2011. Seed dormancy mechanism and dormancy breaking methods of Datura stramonium L. Acta Botanica Boreali-Occidentalia Sinica, 31:683-689). So. the generation time is one year or longer due to the seed bank.
NA

Digitalis purpurea is a facultative biennial, a monocarpic species that can complete their life cycle within 2 years, but where a delay of reproduction until the third or later year is commonly observed because it must reach a threshold size to be able to be vernalized (Sletvold N. 2002. Effects of plant size on reproductive output and offspring performance in the facultative biennial Digitalis purpurea. Journal of Ecology, 90:958-966). While, 19% of seeds germinates in the same year their are release (in autum), 48% germinates in the following spring (Van Baalen J. 1982. Germination ecology and seed population dynamics of Digitalis purpurea. Oecologia, 53:61-67). Germination in autum allow a life cycle of one year, germination in springs allow a life cycle of two years (because vernalization is required). But also is posible that plants germinated in autum do not reach the size threshold required to be vernalized. Generation time computed from transitions matrices in COMPADRE database (Matrices 242803, 242806 in COMPADRE Plant Matrix Database (2021). Available from: https://www.compadre-db.org/Species/46874 [18 May 2021, Version 6.21.1.0]) vary from 3.47 to 7.84 years

The plant species E. vulgare (vipers's bugloss) is a self-compatible monocarpic perennial. Plants flowered at a mean age of 2.7 years on the sparse site and 3.4 years on the dense sites (Klemow KM & Raynal DJ. 1985. Demography of Two Facultative Biennial Plant Species in an Unproductive Habitat. The Journal of Ecology, 73:147-167). Levels of innate seed dormancy vary among populations, germination without cold stratification is low (less than 20%). Seed dispersal begins in mid Summer and continues through mid Autum. Most seedlings emerge in the spring (Klemow KM, Clements DR, Threadgill PF & Cavers PB. 2002. The biology of Canadian weeds. 116. Echium vulgare L. Canadian journal of plant science, 82:235-248). So, generation time is 3.5 years (3 for flowering plus 6 month for stratification). The generation time computed from transition matrix in COMPADRE database (Matrix 242943 in COMPADRE Plant Matrix Database (2021). Available from: https://www.compadre-db.org/Species/46613 [18 May 2021, Version 6.21.1.0]) is consistent, 3.67ys
Not in the paper. Not found in the literature

Not in the paper but, experiment explicitly manipulates generations. Additionally, fo Mimulus guttatus, generation time was computed frome population growth rate estimated in different ecotypes and populations (Peterson ML, Kay KM & Angert AL. 2016. The scale of local adaptation in Mimulus guttatus: comparing life history races, ecotypes, and populations. New Phytologist, 211:345-356.). Seeds of Mimulus guttatus have no dormancy (Macnair MR. 1983. The genetic control of copper tolerance in the yellow monkey flower, Mimulus guttatus. Heredity, 50:283-293.)

Generation time computed with data from Peña- Gómez 2012 (Peña-Gómez, F. T., & Bustamante, R. O. (2012). Life history variation and demography of the invasive plant Eschscholzia californica Cham.(Papaveraceae), in two altitudinal extremes, Central Chile. Gayana Botanica, 69(1), 113-122) according to Stubben & Milligan 2007 (Stubben, C., & Milligan, B. (2007). Estimating and analyzing demographic models using the popbio package in R. Journal of Statistical Software, 22(11), 1-23), by using popbio R package.

The longevity of Festuca idahoensis is at least 60 years (Liston, A. A. R. O. N., Wilson, B. L., Robinson, W. A., Doescher, P. S., Harris, N. R., & Svejcar, T. 2003. The relative importance of sexual reproduction versus clonal spread in an aridland bunchgrass. Oecologia, 137: 216-225), so generation time should be long (maybe more than 30 years) but it is unknow.
NA

The number of years required for a species to start producing seeds is one year according to: Engler R, Randin CF, Vittoz P, Czáka T, Beniston M, Zimmermann NE & Guisan A. 2009. Predicting future distributions of mountain plants under climate change: does dispersal capacity matter?. Ecography, 32:34-45. But this can underestimate the actual generation time because in nature, clones of Festuca rubra can rise more than 400 years old (Harberd, D. J. 1961. Observations on population structure and longevity of Festuca rubra L. New Phytologist, 60: 184-206.), and while older the clone the larger the contribution of seeds to the next generation.

The number of years required for a species to start producing seeds is one year according to: Engler R, Randin CF, Vittoz P, Czáka T, Beniston M, Zimmermann NE & Guisan A. 2009. Predicting future distributions of mountain plants under climate change: does dispersal capacity matter?. Ecography, 32:34-45. But this can underestimate the actual generation time because in nature, clones of Festuca rubra can rise more than 400 years old (Harberd, D. J. 1961. Observations on population structure and longevity of Festuca rubra L. New Phytologist, 60: 184-206.), and while older the clone the larger the contribution of seeds to the next generation.

Seedlings that mostly appear in late autumn or early winter can make appreciable growth especially during mild winters. Individual plants persist until late summer or autumn before the onset of frosty weather. Flowering occurs from May to September (summer) and seed is set from June to October (summer-fall), often after the plant has died. Galium aparine is an annual plant, their requirements for vernalization and seed dormancy are variable among populations (Taylor K. 1999. Galium aparine L. Journal of ecology, 87:713-730). We will assuma a generation time of one year but it could be shorter.

Geranium carolinianum, a winter annual, germinates in Autum and persists as a rosette, close to the ground, until spring. It flowers in Spring, disperses its seeds, and dies before Summer (Roach DA. 1986. Life history variation in Geranium carolinianum. 1. Covariation between characters at different stages of the life cycle. The American Naturalist, 128:47-57). Thir seeds have primary dormancy and, without scariafication, will not germinate before 3.5 months (i.e. the following Autum) (Baskin JM & Baskin CC. 1974. Some eco-physiological aspects of seed dormancy in Geranium carolinianum L. from central Tennessee. Oecologia, 16:209-219). So, its generation time is one year.

Glechoma hederacea is a clonal perennial protohemicryptophyte herb. Vegetative spread is rapid and monocultures covering several square metres are occasionally produced. New ramets produce seeds within a year (Hutchings MJ & Price EA. 1999. Glechoma hederacea L.(Nepeta glechoma Benth., N. hederacea (L.) Trev.). Journal of Ecology, 87:347-364). So, the age at maturity is one year but the true generation time could be much longer.

Generation time of Stipa comata based on demographyc data from West et al 1979, assuming fecundity is proportional to age (West NE, Rea KH & Harniss RO. 1979. Plant demographic studies in sagebrush‐grass communities of southeastern Idaho. Ecology, 60:376-388).

Holocus lanatus, reproduce mostly vegetativelyt, but it produce seeds in the first or second year from sowing, but populations from UK do not produce seeds in the first year (Beddows AR. 1961. Holcus lanatus L. Journal of Ecology, 49: 421-430).
According Maron et al 2004, Ecological Monographs, 74(2):261-280
NA

Impatiens glandulifera is a summer-annual therophyte with no vegetative reproduction. Germination to flowering takes c. 13 weeks, flowering usually continues for 12 weeks. Abundant seed is set each year.  I. glandulifera requires a period of chilling to break dormanc (Beerling DJ & Perrins JM. 1993. Impatiens glandulifera Royle (Impatiens roylei Walp.). Journal of Ecology, 81:367-382)

In the paper the authors guess that 100-130 years represents 50 J. vulgaris generations. Jacobaea vulgaris (synonym Senecio jacobaea) is a monocarpic perennial that spends its first year as a rosette. Flowering may take place in the second year, but is often delayed (vernalization depending on a size threshold). Its seeds do not possess innate dormancy. Most of the individuals flowered in the thirth (2 years old) or in fourth (3 years old) year (Van der Meijden E & van der Waals-Kooi RE. 1979. The Population Ecology of Senecio Jacobaea in a Sand Dune System: I. Reproductive Strategy and the Biennial Habit. The Journal of Ecology, 67:131-153). So, generation time is 2.5 years. Generation time computed from transition matrices from COMPADRE database (Matrices 245528, 245531, 245534, 245537, 245540  in COMPADRE Plant Matrix Database (2021). Available from: https://www.compadre-db.org/Species/46711 [18 May 2021, Version 6.21.1.0]) are quite variable (from 6.31 to 54.8 years). I kept the GT of 2.5 years, but the uncertainty is large.

Jacobaea vulgaris (synonym Senecio jacobaea) is a monocarpic perennial that spends its first year as a rosette. Flowering may take place in the second year, but is often delayed (vernalization depending on a size threshold). Its seeds do not possess innate dormancy. Most of the individuals flowered in the thirth (2 years old) or in fourth (3 years old) year (Van der Meijden E & van der Waals-Kooi RE. 1979. The Population Ecology of Senecio Jacobaea in a Sand Dune System: I. Reproductive Strategy and the Biennial Habit. The Journal of Ecology, 67:131-153). So, generation time is 2.5 years. Generation time computed from transition matrices from COMPADRE database (Matrices 245528, 245531, 245534, 245537, 245540 in COMPADRE Plant Matrix Database (2021). Available from: https://www.compadre-db.org/Species/46711 [18 May 2021, Version 6.21.1.0]) are quite variable (from 6.31 to 54.8 years). I kept the GT of 2.5 years, but the uncertainty is large.

Koeleria macrantha flowers in the first summer after autumn germination and the number of inflorescences at this time is quite low: in cultivation in a good loam this was between 30 and 40, but by the end of 2 years some tussocks had over 200 inflorescences (range 30-291, mean 101.4 ã 13.5). Koeleria macrantha produces a transient seed bank during the summer, when the caryopses are shed, these germinate nearly synchronously in the autumn: there is a complete absence of germinable seeds during spring and early summer (Dixon JM. 2000. Koeleria macrantha (Ledeb.) Schultes (K. alpigena Domin, K. cristata (L.) Pers. pro parte, K. gracilis Pers., K. albescens auct. non DC.). Journal of Ecology, 88:709-726). So the minimum generation time is one year. However, more aged plants produce much more seeds, as we have only information for two years old plants we, comute the genretation time as (1·35+2·101)/(35+101)=1.73. Transition matrices in COMPADRE database are based on tillers (not plants/genets) and include clonal reproduction, so Infinite generation time is estimated.

Koeleria macrantha (syn Koeleria cristata) flowers in the first summer after autumn germination and the number of inflorescences at this time is quite low: in cultivation in a good loam this was between 30 and 40, but by the end of 2 years some tussocks had over 200 inflorescences (range 30-291, mean 101.4 ã 13.5). Koeleria macrantha produces a transient seed bank during the summer, when the caryopses are shed, these germinate nearly synchronously in the autumn: there is a complete absence of germinable seeds during spring and early summer (Dixon JM. 2000. Koeleria macrantha (Ledeb.) Schultes (K. alpigena Domin, K. cristata (L.) Pers. pro parte, K. gracilis Pers., K. albescens auct. non DC.). Journal of Ecology, 88:709-726). So the minimum generation time is one year. However, more aged plants produce much more seeds, as we have only information for two years old plants we, comute the genretation time as (1·35+2·101)/(35+101)=1.73. Transition matrices in COMPADRE database are based on tillers (not plants/genets) and include clonal reproduction, so Infinite generation time is estimated.

Two generations take place in each year and seeds have no dormancy (Marks M & Prince S. 1981. Influence of Germination Date on Survival and Fecundity in Wild Lettuce Lactuca Serriola. Oikos, 36:326-330., Weaver SE & Downs MP. 2003. The biology of Canadian weeds. 122. Lactuca serriola L. Can. J. Plant Sci. 83:619–628). Transition matrices in COMPADRE database are based on less than a year of observation and are incomplete.

Lepidium draba is a perennial herb, it has a root system that consists of vertical and lateral roots from which new rosettes and flowering shoots arise. Lepidium draba survives and spreads primarily by extremely persistent roots. These roots, with abundant food reserves, overwinter and produce new shootsin the spring (MULLIGAN GA & FINDLAY JN. 1974. The biology of Canadian weeds. 3. Cardaria draba, C. chalepensis, and C. pubescens. Canadian Journal of Plant Science, 54:149-160. Scurfield G. 1962. Cardaria Draba (L.) Desv. The Journal of Ecology, 50:489-499). New plants (grown from seeds) lasted two years to produce flowers (Selleck GW. 1965. An Ecological Study of Lens- and Globe-Podded Hoary Cresses in Saskatchewan. Weeds, 13:1-5). So, the minimum generation time (it underestimates the actuall generation time) is two years. While  most  individuals of Lepidium draba were relatively young (2 to 4 years old), occasional individuals were found to be up to 8 years old (Dietz H & Schweingruber FH. 2002. Annual rings in native and introduced forbs of lower Michigan, USA. Canadian Journal of Botany, 80:642-649). Individuals up to 10 years hold were found (Dietz H. 2002. Plant invasion patches–reconstructing pattern and process by means of herb-chronology. Biological Invasions, 4:211-222). Assuming a compensation between mortality (with age) and increase of fecundity (with age, it still underestimated generation time), the generation time would be 6 years.

Not in the paper but, experiment explicitly manipulates generations. Additionally, for Lolium rigidum, plants reach maturity at 3-4 month after germination (Chauhan BS, Gill G & Preston C. 2006. Tiller dynamics, growth, and persistency of Lolium perenne L. and of Lolium rigidum Gaud. Australian Journal of Agricultural Research, 15:9-20.). So a generation time of 1 year seems accurate.

Lupinus bicolor is an annual, seeds require to be scattered to germinate and flowering depends on day length (Dunn DB. 1956. The Breeding Systems of Lupinus, Group Micranthi. American Midland Naturalist, 55:443-472). A generation time of one year seems accurate.

"The species has been described as a facultative annual because it can set seed in one growing season (Shipley and Parent 1991, Johansson and Keddy 1991), however, this description is misleading because the species is not semelparous. Lythrum salicaria is a perennial, with annual stems arising from a perennating rootstock. There are no reports in the literature concerning the longevity of single genets." (Mal TR, Lovett-Doust J, Lovett-Doust L & Mulligan GA. 1992. The biology of Canadian weeds. 100. Lythrum salicaria. Canadian Journal of Plant Science, 72:1305-1330.). Comersial apple trees have their first fruits by the secon year (Neilsen GH, Parchomchuk P, Wolk WD & Lau OL. 1993. Growth and mineral composition of newly planted apple trees following fertigation with N and P. Journal of the American Society for Horticultural Science, 118:50-53)

Medicago polymorpha is a winter annual (germinating in Autumn, overwintering, flowering in spring, and dying by summer), additionally seeds require vernalization to germinate. As a consequence, the cycle, from seed to seed, takes 2 years to compleate. (Wagner, L. K., & Spira, T. P. (1994). Germination, recruitment and survival in the weedy annual Medicago polymorpha in successive wet and dry years. American Midland Naturalist, 98-108.

While individual trees can live over 100 years (Dray 2003), they can become reproductive within 1–2 years (Meskimen 1962, Vardaman 1994). So, a generation time of 2 years is a serious underestimation.

In Melilotus officinalis, annual individuals overwinter as seeds, biennial individuals overwinter alternatively as seeds and as thick tap root. Natural vegetative reproduction has not been observed. Almost all seedlings appearing in late summer, autumn and early winter die before spring.  Many seedlings appearing in late winter also perish but occasional groups survive and give rise to plants which flower during the same year. In contrast, seedlings appearing in Spring have the best chance of survival but invariably are biennial. (Turkington RA, Cavers PB, Empel E. 1978. The biology of Canadian weeds. 29. Melilotus alba Desr. and M. officinalis (L.) Lam. Can J Plant Sci, 58:523–537). Plants always die after flowering (monocarpic). Seeds have a long lifespan (40 years) and require scarification to germinate. However, seeds from a similar species (Melilotus albus) is scarified by frozen temperatures and a high proportion of intact seeds germinates in spring after overwintering in the soil (Zhang Y, Zhang K, Ji Y & Tao J. 2020. Physical dormancy and soil seed bank dynamics in seeds of Melilotus albus (Fabaceae). Flora, 266, 151600). So, a 2 years generation time may underestimate the actual generation time but not so far.

in the paper: “each year was calculated as 0.72 generations, on the basis of the weighted average of annual and biennial life histories exhibited by plant genotypes in 2007”. However for further genration time of this species: In Oenothera biennis, plants die after flowering (monocarpic). All plants of two years old (3º year of observation) flowered or died. More than 75% (probably more than 85%) of flowering plants are 2 years old (Gross KL. 1981. Predictions of fate from rosette size in four "biennial" plant species: Verbascum thapsus, Oenothera biennis, Daucus carota, and Tragopogon dubius. Oecologia, 48:209–213, Tables 1 and 2). Also, the bigger plants, so the more fecund are the older. Seeds do not show primary dormancy (Baskin CC, Baskin JM. 1994. Germination requirements of Oenothera biennis seeds during burial under natural seasonal temperature cycles. Canadian Journal of Botany, 72:779-782). Most of the seeds germinate in Spring and plants flower also in spring. So generation time is 2-3 years (two of vegetative growing and one year to germination of the new cohort).

Pastinaca sativa is a perenial monocarpic species (Baskin JM & Baskin CM. 1979. Studies on the autecology and population biology of the weedy monocarpic perennial, Pastinaca sativa. The Journal of Ecology 67:601-610). Seeds germinate in spring and early summer. The first summer a plant develops a leaf rosette and a strong taproot. The following or some later spring it sends up a flowering stalk (Thompson JN & Price PW. 1977. Plant plasticity, phenology, and herbivore dispersion: wild parsnip and the parsnip webworm. Ecology 58: 1112-1119). Seeds seem not to have dormancy but use to germinate in the next growing season, mainly depending on weather conditions (Hendrix SD. 1984. Variation in seed weight and its effects on germination in Pastinaca sativa L.(Umbelliferae). American Journal of Botany 71:795-802). From de demographyc data from Baskin 1979 we estimated the generation time as 1.75 years. Takeing into account the delay in the germination of seeds we think a generation time of 2 years seems a reasonable approximation.

Plantago lanceolata (ribwort plantain) is a short-lived perennial species with a basal rosette. It germinates in the fall and spring and flowers in mid summer. It remains green all year. Only 7% of the population remained alive after 4.5yr. Individuals in the field flowered for the first  time in Spring of year 2 (one year old). The risk of mortality varied across levels of reproduction and across years. In the first year of reproduction, individuals with the largest number of inflorescences had the highest mortality. Individuals with minimal or no reproduction had lower mortality. In later years, this hierarchy was reversed such that the class of individuals with the largest level of reproduction had the lowest mortality. Generation time computed from the life table built with data from Roach & Gampe 2004 (Roach DA & Gampe J. 2004. Age‐Specific Demography in Plantago: Uncovering Age‐Dependent Mortality in a Natural Population. The American Naturalist, 164:60–69).

Not in the paper. See Gibeault VA. 1971. Perenniality in Poa annua L. and Law R, Bradshaw AD, Putwain PD. 1977. Life-history variation in Poa annua. Evolution, 31:233-246. There is huge variability in the life history of Poa annua, however, according to Finite rate of increase estimated by Law et al 1977 generation time could be as short as 0.104 years. But, according to Gibeault 1971, seed dormancy varies between 0 and 3 months in different populations and varieties, also winter temperatures below 4.5 ºC preclude germination. So, we estimate a conservative GT of 6 month.

Life expectancy of Elymus spicatus is up to 65 years (Treshow M & Harper K. 1974. Longevity of Perennial Forbs and Grasses. Oikos, 25:93-96). Seeds begin germination in fall, bluebunchwheatgrass does not require cold stratification (Link SO, Cruz RO, Harper BL, Jones JD, Penney BL. 2011. Fort Collins, CO, USA: USDA Forest Service. RMRS-P-65. p.159–167). Assuming that each age class contributes equally to seed production (i.e. mortality is compensated by increase in size and seed production, which tend to underestimates the contribution of old plants), so generation time results the half of lifespan (i.e. 32 years).

Rorippa austriaca is a polycarpic, perennial hemicryptophyte. It has the potential to reproduce sexually but was found to spread mainly by vegetative propagation via sprouting from lateral roots. Following plagiotropic growth the lateral roots bend downward and the vertical parts become stark and might eventually develop into tap-roots and produce new shoots and second order lateral roots. In Spring, the species develops flowering stalks. The species flowers copiously in late Spring early Summer. Roroppa austriaca seems to be a rather long-lived species, with fragments of clones attaining ages of at least 13 years (Dietz H, Köhler A & Ullmann I. 2002. Regeneration growth of the invasive clonal forb Rorippa austriaca (Brassicaceae) in relation to fertilization and interspecific competition. Plant Ecology, 158:171-182). Assuming a compensation between mortality and increase in size (and fertility) we estimate a generation time of 6.5 years (possibly an underestimation of the actual generation time).

Rumex acetosa is a polycarpic perennial which possesses a limited capacity for vegetative propagation (Voesenek LACJ & Blom CWPM. 1992. Germination and emergence ofRumexin river flood-plains. I. Timing of germination and seedbank characteristics. Acta Botanica Neerlandica, 41: 319–329). The mature plant overwinters as a basal rosette and produces one or more inflorescences in spring. The inflorescences elongate at the beginning of April and bloom through April and May. The seeds mature from late April onward, just after flowering. Therefore, flowering and seeding overlap within individual inflorescence stems and branches (Matsuhisa S & Ushimaru A. 2019. Does sexual dimorphism exist in flowering phenology traits in anemophilous dioecious species? A test with Rumex acetosa. American journal of botany, 106: 1356-1364). No dormancy was observed in Rumex acetosa, and seeds survive in optimal conditions at least 3 years (Steinbauer GP & Grigsby B. 1960. Dormancy and germination of the docks (Rumex spp.). Proceedings of the Association of Official Seed Analysts, 50: 112-117). A generation time of 2 years can underestimate the actual generation time.

Rumex acetosellaL. (sheep’s sorrel, red sorrel) is acommon herbaceous perennial species which spreads by seeds and a shallow creeping root system. The role of seedling establishment in population maintenance is considered minor with established populations maintained predominantly by vegetative reproduction of ramets from the creeping root system. no seedlings flowered in the year of emergence (White SN, Boyd NS & Van Acker RC. 2014. Demography ofRumex acetosellain lowbush blueberry (Vaccinium angustifolium). Weed Research, 54:377–387). From data of White et al 2014, I produced a transition matrix and computed the generation time.

Rumex crispus is a perennial species. It is able to establish quickly from seed, also has a persistent taproot system, a massive production of seed that remain viable in the seed bank for decades. R. crispus seedlings can emerge throughout the growing season and seeds that remain on the  parent plant over winter posses a certain level of dormancy, leading to later and more intermittent emergence compared to the seeds dispersed in  autumn. Tillage that leads to fragmentation of the root system can stimulate sprouting of new shoots from the regenerative tissue of the taproot. Severed top fragments of roots sprouted faster and produced more shoot biomass than intact rootstocks. Germination of R. crispus seeds is stimulated by light and fluctuating temperatures. Seedling emergence can occur in flushes during the whole vegetation period, depending on weather conditions. Once the juvenile plant is established, the development goes through three phases: the rosette phase, the elongation phase, and the inflorescence phase. Depending on resource availability, R. crispus may flower in its first year or, more commonly, remain in the rosette phase through its first winter. Flowering takes place in late Spring to early Autum, occasional single plants can flower twice in a season. Surviving plants will overwinter as a rosette and can reproduce again in one or several years. Longevity of R. obtusifolius has been reported up to 5 years. Emergence from seeds sown in autumn showed a distinct peak in Spring, while peak emergence for seeds sown in early spring did not occur until late early Summer. Total mortality during the four year period of the field experiment was 24 percent, and total proportion of plants reaching a reproductive stage (i.e. flowered at least once) was 23 percent (Pye A. 2008. Ecological studies of Rumex crispus L. Propagation, competition and demography. Doctoral Thesis, Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences, Faculty of Natural Resources and Agricultural Sciences, Department of Crop Production Ecology. Upsala). Generation time was computed from demographyc data in Pye 2008, assuming a lifespan of 5 years, a life table was built and generation time was computed.

Senecio inaequidens is a shortlived perennial that reaches maturity in its first year of life (Ernst WHO. 1998. Invasion, dispersal and ecology of the South African neophyte Senecio inaequidens in The Netherlands: from wool alien to railway and road alien. Acta Botanica Neerlandica, 47:131-151). Senecio pterophorus is a perennial plant and first flowering time is about 110 days (Colomer-Ventura F, Martínez-Vilalta J, Zuccarini P, Escolà A, Armengot L, Castells E. 2015. Contemporary evolution of an invasive plant is associated with climate but not with herbivory. Functional Ecology, 29:1475-1485). Senecio sylvaticus is an annual, mostly autogamous plant. Within the group of annual Senecio species, S. sylvaticus is not as strict summer annual as the co-occurring S. viscosus, but has also not such a variable seasonality as S. vulgaris. S. sylvaticus is rooting in the litter layer (A00) and fermentation layer (A0) and is very unproductive on mineral soils. Achenes of S. sylvaticus genninated in Autum or in Spring. From late Spring to mid Summer no germination was observed. In addition to the two different periods of gennination, there was a great difference in plant biomass of both life forms in spring. The biomass of the winter annual life forms was more than ten fold that of the summer annual life form in the last days of May. Under natural conditions, the summer annual populations did flower from summer to autum. (Ernst, W. H. O. (1989). Selection of winter and summer annual life forms in populations of Senecio sylvaticus L. Flora, 182(3-4), 221-231)

S. vulgaris is a summer or winter annual, reproducing only by seed. S. vulgaris is monocarpic (Robinson DE, O’Donovan JT, Sharma MP, Doohan DJ and Figueroa R. 2003. The Biology of Canadian Weeds. 123. Senecio vulgaris L. Can. J. Plant Sci. 83: 629–644)

Richards (1997) have estimated average generation time in natural populations of S. latifolia to be approximately 1.5 years by direct census of marked plants (Richards CM. 1997. The ecological genetics of population establishment in Silene alba. PhD  Dissertation,  Duke  University, Durham, NC, USA.)

Solidago altissima, is a perennial. Most ramets emerge in Spring from the apical tips of underground rhizomes, and increase in height until mid Summer, at which time flower heads begin to form. The apical tips of some rhizomes emerge the previous season, but the leaves of such rhizomes do not expand until spring (i.e. there are no overwintering rosettes). Rhizome growth is sympodial. The above-ground portion of ramets die over winter, and their daughter rhizomes remain dormant until the following spring. Ramets are not produced at the same node in successive years, so genet survival depends upon the new ramets that emerge in the spring from overwintering rhizomes. Although above-ground shoots die after one season, roots and rhizome connections persist for up to 5-6 years (fragmentation, not death) (Cain ML. 1990. Models of Clonal Growth in Solidago Altissima. The Journal of Ecology, 78:27-46). Clones of S. canadensis increase in both size and density and can persist for a considerable number of years, estimated at more than 100 yr (Werner, P. A., GROSS, R. S., & BRADBURY, I. K. (1980). THE BIOLOGY OF CANADIAN WEEDS.: 45. Solidago canadensis L. Canadian Journal of Plant Science, 60:1393-1409). Germination within the established vegetation was very rare: only 12 out of 150000 experimentally sown seeds (0.008%) became seedlings. The survival and growth of seedlings transplanted into closed vegetation increased with age and developmental stage. Nevertheless, no transplants flowered during the 24 months over which their fate was followed (Meyer AH & Schmid B. 1999. Seed dynamics and seedling establishment in the invading perennial Solidago altissima under different experimental treatments. Journal of Ecology, 87:28-41). So, it seems the generation time in Solidago altissima should be very long but we did not find any approximation. COMPADRE database transition matrix (Matrix 245611 in COMPADRE Plant Matrix Database (2021). Available from: https://www.compadre-db.org/Species/46727 [21 May 2021, Version 6.21.1.0]) leads to a generation time of 6723 years.

Solidago gigantea is very simmilar to Solidago altissima (see Solidago altissima GTimeNotes). Solidago gigantea is a tall, erect perennial herb with annual aboveground shoots and persistent belowground rhizomes. Solidago gigantea produces long-creeping plagiotropic, mostly purple or reddish rhizomes, mostly within the upper 10–20 cm of soil. In total, 3–50 rhizomes per ramet emerge close to the base of shoots from the previous year. Higher numbers have been observed after disturbances. Production of seeds, new shoots and new rhizomes occurs every year, and all aboveground shoots die back in autumn. Free carbohydrates are accumulated in the rhizome before the dormant period. Seedlings have never been observed within established patches of S. gigantea, suggesting that seeds are primarily important for long-distance dispersal and the colonization of new sites. However, seedlings may appear after a spring mowing, suggesting that successful establishment is dependent upon open conditions. In most cases, however, population increase is primarily the result of clonal growth. The relative significance of sexual reproduction increases with the age of the clone, whereas clonal growth is most essential during the first years after establishment. Individual clones are often easy to distinguish and frequently achieve 2–5 m diameter. Larger, older clones may contain thousands of ramets. Occasionally clones form ‘fairy circles’ around the initial centre of the genet. Under good conditions, almost all plants reproduce in their first year, and a single ramet produces up to 19,000 achenes. Under resource limited conditions, sexual reproduction is reduced to the benefit of vegetative growth (Weber E & Jakobs G. 2005. Biological flora of central Europe: Solidago gigantea Aiton. Flora - Morphology, Distribution, Functional Ecology of Plants, 200:109–118). Generation time should be long but I did not find any estimation. However, Meyer et al 2005 (Meyer G, Clare R, Weber E. 2005. An experimental test of the evolution of increased competitive ability hypothesis in goldenrod, Solidago gigantea. Oecologia, 144:299-307) observed that almost all plants grown from seeds flowered in the secon year, more than a half flowered in the first year. So, in newly colonized areas a generation time of 2 years can be assumed. This would be a severe underestimation for established populations.

Trifolium pratense seedlings appeared from March to May (namely spring cohort) and from September to November (namely autumn cohort) every year. Estimated seedling density ranged yearly from 18 to 1,215 seedlings/m 2 in the spring cohorts and from 1 to 245 seedlings/m 2 in the autumn cohorts, with an average of 199 and 86 seedlings/m2 , respectively. Half-life ranged yearly from 4 to 63 days for the spring cohorts and from 33 to 248 days for the autumn cohorts, with an average of 42 and 135 days, respectively. Of the 13,485 seedlings marked, no individuals survived for more than 4 years. Most of the individuals undergoing flowering (hereafter referred to as “flowering individuals”) originated from the autumn cohorts. Thirty-two percent of the survivors began to flower in the first summer after their appearance. Ratio of flowering individuals to survivors rose to 81% in the second summer and fell to 50% in the third summer. Although the number of flowering individuals decreased yearly, the ratio peaked 2 years after seedling appearance in both kinds of cohorts. (SAKANOUE S. 2002. Seedling appearance, survival andflowering of Trifolium pratense in a cutting meadow. Japan Agricultural Research Quarterly, 36:235–241). Table of life and generation time were computed based on demographyc information from this paper.

Tussilago farfara is a rhizomatous perennial. Germination takes place shortly after the seeds are shed in April or May (spring), and in suitable habitats a tap root is quickly developed. During the first summer contractile adventitious roots develop on the lowest nodes of the stem, followed shortly by rhizomes, initiated in the same region. By the autumn several large leaves may be present, rhizomes well developed, and inflorescence ('flower') buds will usually have been formed. In favourable situations vegetative reproduction occurs in the first season, the tips of certain rhizomes growing upwards to produce new plants. During the winter the leaves die, and all that is usually visible at the soil surface is a cluster of flower buds on the 'stock'. The stock is the non-rhizomatous portion of the stem, which bears the leaves in summer and the flowers in the following spring: it is normally short and thick, with very close internodes (Raunkiaer 1934). The flower buds continue their development during the winter, and early in the following spring the peduncles elongate rapidly and the flowers open. Seed dispersal occurs in April and May (spring). During the flowering period leaves are expanded by the new vegetative shoots at the tips of those rhizomes which were formed in the previous year. The flowering stock and the peduncles normally die after the seeds are shed, leading to fragmentation of the rhizome system. The new vegetative plants follow the same cycle of development as those in the previous year. It follows that normally rhizomes initiated in one year produce leafy shoots in the second year, and these shoots produce flowers in the third year (2 years old) of life of the rhizomes. After this they usually die, leaving further growth to new rhizome (Ogden J. 1974. The Reproductive Strategy of Higher Plants: II. The Reproductive Strategy of Tussilago Farfara L. The Journal of Ecology, 62:291-324). Generation Time is considered as the number of years required for a species to start producing seeds (this can underestimate the actual generation time) according to: Engler R, Randin CF, Vittoz P, Czáka T, Beniston M, Zimmermann NE & Guisan A. 2009. Predicting future distributions of mountain plants under climate change: does dispersal capacity matter?. Ecography, 32:34-45.

Ulex europaeus starts to reproduce at 2 or 3 years old. It lives up to 30 years old. It follows the −3/2 law of self-thinning (Rees M & Hill RL. 2001. Large-scale disturbances, biological control and the dynamics of gorse populations. J Appl Ecol 38:364–377). We assume that an increase in fecundity with age compensates for mortality, so the contribution of each age to the next generation is constant. This assumption probably underestimates the generation time, but less than just using the age at maturity.

Veronica hederifolia is a winter annual, most seedlings appeared in November- January (late Autumn to early winter).Flowering starts in March. Most of the individuals present at that time set seed and all had died by July (Summer). There was then a gap of 3-4 months before the next generation started to germinate and cohorts of seedlings continued to appear until April (Vegetative stage spans less than one year). Low temperatures in the winter appeared not to harm the seedlings of this species. Seeds require cold stratification to germinate (Boutin C & Harper JL. 1991. A Comparative Study of the Population Dynamics of Five Species of Veronica in Natural Habitats. The Journal of Ecology, 79:199-221). So, a generation time of one year is accurate.
